is, that all pastors in everie congrega tion should teach sobrietie, temperan cie, and the true fast in deede: not pre suming to prescribe any lawes for the choice of meates or times, but leaving that free to every man & nation, who undoubtedly will have an especial eye to temper theselves from the thinges, by which they perceive ye their health wilbe indaungered, but most of all in the time when the fleshe beginneth to waxe over wanton, or whe some great peril hangeth over their head. For the time of fasting is not proroged till an appointed number of yeares or dayes be expired, but til the loosenes or wan tonnesse of the flesh, temptations, or motions be utterly brideled. Fastings being so ordered, as they be the exerci ses of godlines, obteine great praise in deede in the Church of the Lord. THus much hitherto touching fa sting. Now so that uppe this seventh precept, I say it forbiddeth al intem perauncie, it commaundeth dolinesse, and the cleane and lawefull use of all the members of the whole bodie: and therefore in this short precept there is conteined a good part of the doctrine of Christ and his Apostles. For Paule to the Thessalonians sayeth: We be seech you brethren, and exhort you by the Lorde Jesus, that yee increase more and more, as yee have received of us, howe ye ought to walke, and to
please God. For ye knowe what com
maundementes wee gave you by the
Lorde Jesus. For this is the will of God
even your holinesse, that ye should ab
steine from fornication, that everie
one of you should knowe how to pos
sesse his vessel in holinesse and honour,
not in the lust of concupiscence as the
Gentiles which knewe not GOD.
God is a revenger of all such as wee
have forewarned you and testified.
For God hath not called us unto un
cleannesse, but unto holinesse. And
straight way after againe: The God
of peace sanctifie you throughout,
that your whoale spirite, and soule,
and bodie, may bee preserved blame
lesse in the comming of our Lord Jesus
Christ.
I have againe my brethren, passed
beyond the appointed time of an ordi
nary sermon, staying you longer than
I am wont to doe. Pardon this fault,
for (I hope) I have not troubled you
almost two whole houres, without
profiting you any whit at all. Make
your prayers now, & depart in peace.
By the helpe and wil of God I will
within these fewe dayes adde the rest
of the tenne commaundements.
The grace of our Lorde and
savior Jesus Christ be
with you all.
